Most melees are NOT heavily twinked.  Many are, but most are just very well equipped.<br>
<br>
Ykesha's, Icetooth Claws, Wurmslayers, swords of skyfire, canes of tranquil are all standard twinkish weapons that players that work hard to earn money can buy around level 30.<br>
<br>
Any haste items are still out of range for any pre-40 player unless they are a die-hard trader or ebay-twink themselves.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  However, the main point I am trying, unsuccessfully, to make, is that due to the number and diversity of players at the lower levels, and the relative strength of mobs versus the players, that the comparison of the strength of one particular twink to another does not matter as much as the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  direct</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> comparison between that character and the mobs he is facing.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
If there is a player-competitive argument to be made, you must set up fair conditions under which to compare.  This poster is talking about up to level 27, and is observing the travel related hardships that most warriors this level face.  You can't arbitrarily give a warrior tboots and kael armor and compare him to a wizard a fishbone necklace and a rusty dagger.  <br>
<br>
Yes, melee twinking is more effective than wizard twinking, but that doesn't matter, because either way both classes become overpowered against the mobs they are intended to fight.  Encounters are trivialized no matter what way you look at it, and the game turns into a race to 50.  When that happens, you've turned the game into something it was not meant to be.<br>
<br>
Personally, I view the caster/melee competition for groups basically meaningless for the first 20 levels.  All classes can solo to some extent.  Some better than others, but it is possible for everyone.  Groups happen most often as a random meetings, or players go to oasis and LFG.  If you can't get a group in oasis, there are lots of other places you can adventure and earn xp.  There are lots of other players on norrath at that level that aren't wearing Cloaks of Flame and wielding Frostbringers.  So long as you can defeat mobs solo and with any group makeup, you're good to go.<br>
<br>
Slowly, it begins to matter more and more, as full pickup groups become more common, as mobs become more difficult, and as the penalties for failure become more severe.  If you're a level 40 caster and really cannot get into a standard level 40 group because it is full of twinks, and because any other class would be better than yours, then ya there is probably a problem somewhere.<br>
<br>
